th the sociologist’s search for overarching claims, the book explores the systemic connections amongst three substantive areas to explain why contrasting traditions of racial violence took such firm root in the American South and South Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and social action. 0aArtxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican South.  aSouth Africa.  abureaucratic culture.  alynch culture.  arace relations.  aracial killing.  aracial state.  aracial violence.  awhite Southerners.  awhite supremacy.1 aEvans, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779294540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792945423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792945/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles